# William Wentworth‑Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam  

**The Right Honourable** [The_Right_Honourable](/The_Right_Honourable)  
**Earl Fitzwilliam** [Earl_Fitzwilliam]  
**PC** [Privy_Council_(United_Kingdom)]  

Portrait by **William Owen** [William_Owen_(painter)], 1817  

---

## Early life and background  

William Wentworth‑Fitzwilliam (30 May 1748 – 8 February 1833), styled Viscount Milton until 1756, was a British **Whig** [Whig_(British_political_party)] **statesman** [Politician] of the late 18th and early 19th centuries. In 1782 he inherited the estates of his uncle **Charles Watson‑Wentworth, 2nd Marquess of Rockingham** [Charles_Watson‑Wentworth,_2nd_Marquess_of_Rockingham], making him one of the richest people in Britain. He played a leading part in Whig politics until the 1820s.  

Born the son of **William Fitzwilliam, 3rd Earl Fitzwilliam** [William_Fitzwilliam,_3rd_Earl_Fitzwilliam] and Lady Anne Watson‑Wentworth, he was the nephew of the celebrated Prime Minister **Charles Watson‑Wentworth, 2nd Marquess of Rockingham** [Charles_Watson‑Wentworth,_2nd_Marquess_of_Rockingham]. He inherited the two **Earls of Fitzwilliam** titles (in the Peerages of Great Britain and of Ireland) in 1756 at the age of eight upon his father’s death.  

His education at **Eton College** [Eton_College] produced a lifelong friendship with **Charles James Fox** [Charles_James_Fox] and **Lord Morpeth** [Frederick_Howard,_5th_Earl_of_Carlisle]. His Eton tutor, **Edward Young**, wrote to Lady Fitzwilliam on 25 July 1763 praising his “exceeding good understanding, and … most amiable disposition and temper” [1]. Lord Carlisle (Lord Morpeth) even composed a poem celebrating Fitzwilliam’s virtues:  

> “Say, will Fitzwilliam ever want a heart,  
> Cheerful his ready blessings to impart? …” [2]  

A portrait of his maternal uncle, the Marquess of Rockingham, painted by **Sir Joshua Reynolds** [Sir_Joshua_Reynolds], 1766, further cemented the family’s artistic legacy.  

---

## Grand Tour and early travels  

In October 1764 Fitzwilliam embarked on his **Grand Tour** [Grand_tour] accompanied by a clergyman, Thomas Crofts, nominated by Dr Edward Barnard, headmaster of Eton. He found France “a set of low, mean, impertinent people” whose behaviour was “so intolerable that it is absolutely impossible for me to associate with them” [3], prompting an early departure to Switzerland. He returned to England in early 1766, resuming his travels only in December of that year.  

By May 1767 he was in Italy, writing from **Genoa** [Genoa] that “I like this place beyond expression” [4]. Between the summers of 1767 and 1768 he visited paintings in **Verona** [Verona], the regatta in **Venice** [Venice], and the galleries in **Padua** [Padua], **Bologna** [Bologna], and **Florence** [Florence]. His taste in art was guided by **Sir Horace Mann** [Sir_Horace_Mann,_1st_Baronet] in Florence and **William Hamilton** [William_Hamilton_(diplomat)] in **Naples** [Naples]. He returned to England in 1768 with fourteen paintings—eight **Canalettos** [Canaletto] and works from the **Bolognese School** [Bolognese_School_(painting)], including pieces by **Guercino** [Guercino] and **Guido Reni** [Guido_Reni] [5].  

The journey concluded with a treacherous crossing of the Alps, through Switzerland, Mannheim, and Paris, finally reaching England in January 1769 [6].  

---

## Inheritance, wealth, and estates  

Fitzwilliam’s inheritance in 1782 comprised the **Wentworth Woodhouse** [Wentworth_Woodhouse] estate—the largest mansion in the country—as well as vast lands across Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, Yorkshire, Norfolk, and an Irish estate of 66,000 acres [66,000_acres]. His annual income from these properties was roughly **£6,900** in 1768, rising to **£115,000** by 1827 after the exploitation of coal mines [11].  

His coal operations were particularly lucrative: profits climbed from **£1,480** in 1780 to **£22,500** by 1825, placing him among the nation’s leading coal owners.  

---

## Landlordship and philanthropy  

As a landlord, Fitzwilliam distinguished himself by reducing rents, cancelling arrears during lean years, and providing cheap food, free coal, blankets, and other charitable aid to the elderly. His chaplain noted that “he was ever giving alms to the poor … the tale of woe was never told to him in vain” [12]. He also sponsored **friendly societies** [Friendly_society] and **savings banks** [Savings_bank_(Britain)] to encourage thrift among the working class.  

Leisure activities included hunting, racehorse breeding, and patronage of the turf. At the 1827 Doncaster Races, he arrived with “two coaches and six, and sixteen outriders,” matching the Duke of Devonshire’s entourage and thereafter “kept the thing up ever since” [13].  

---

## Early political career  

Entering the **House of Lords** [House_of_Lords] after his inheritance, Fitzwilliam attended “almost every notable debate” and signed “nearly every protest which the opposition used” but never delivered a speech during **Lord North** [Frederick_North,_Lord_North]’s premiership [8]. He supported **John Wilkes** in his parliamentary fight and backed the **American Colonies** [Thirteen_Colonies] during the War of Independence, urging Lord Rockingham in July 1776 to send a remonstrance to the King “so the Americans would see that there is still in the country a body of men of the first rank and importance, who would still wish to govern them according to the old policy” [9].  

His first speech on 5 December 1782 criticized the administration of **Lord Shelburne** [William_Pitt_the_Younger] on the concession of American independence. He became a leading supporter of the **Fox‑North coalition**, being offered the Lord Lieutenancy of Ireland and a revived **Marquessate of Rockingham** by the **Duke of Portland** [William_Cavendish-Bentinck,_3rd_Duke_of_Portland]; however, he declined the latter and was not overly concerned with the new title, which the King would not grant anyway [18].  

His maiden speech on 30 June 1783 opposed **William Pitt the Younger**’s Bill to reform public offices, drawing praise from **Horace Walpole** [Horace_Walpole] for his “good sense” and “character” [19].  

---

## Portraiture  

In 1785 Sir **Joshua Reynolds** painted a magnificent full‑length portrait of Fitzwilliam, later engraved by **Joseph Grozer** in 1786. The work, set against a turbulent sky, alludes both to the emotional turmoil following his uncle’s death and the political upheavals of 1783. It also reflects his broader responsibilities as a landowner and patron of the arts [29].  

---

## Lord Lieutenant of Ireland (1794–1795)  

Appointed **Lord Lieutenant of Ireland** [Lord_Lieutenant_of_Ireland] on 10 August 1794, Fitzwilliam arrived in **Balbriggan** [Balbriggan] on 4 January 1795. He immediately confronted a wave of **Defenderism** [Defenders_(Ireland)] violence across counties **Westmeath**, **Meath**, **Longford**, and **Cavan**.  

His policy agenda centered on **Catholic Emancipation** [Catholic_emancipation] and the dismantling of the **Protestant Ascendancy** [Protestant_Ascendancy], believing that granting Catholics greater rights would reconcile them to British rule and thwart Jacobin sympathies. He offered several ecclesiastical appointments, including the **Primacy of Ireland** to the **Bishop of Waterford and Lismore** [Bishop_of_Waterford_and_Lismore] and **Richard Murray** to the **Provost of Trinity College Dublin** [Trinity_College_Dublin].  

However, his reformist stance alarmed **John Beresford**, the leading advocate of Protestant Ascendancy, who was removed from office on 9 January 1795. The **Duke of Portland** and Prime Minister **William Pitt the Younger** eventually recalled Fitzwilliam on 23 February 1795 after a series of political clashes over emancipation and governance [98‑100].  

---

## Opposition and coalition involvement (1795–1806)  

After his recall, Fitzwilliam withdrew from active office, declaring himself “unconnected with any political party” [116]. Yet he remained a pivotal figure in Whig circles, supporting **Burke** against **Fox** and **Sheridan** during the debates over the French Revolution. He financed Burke’s parliamentary seat at **Malton** [Malton_(UK_Parliament_constituency)] and corresponded extensively with him, praising **Reflections on the Revolution in France** [Reflections_on_the_Revolution_in_France] as “almost universally admired and approved” [42‑43].  

When **Pitt** formed the **Pitt–Portland coalition** in 1794, Fitzwilliam accepted the post of **Lord President of the Council** [Lord_President_of_the_Council] on 3 July 1794, delivering his acceptance with “a heavy heart” [81]. He later served as **Minister without Portfolio** [Minister_without_portfolio_(United_Kingdom)] in the **Ministry of All the Talents** [Ministry_of_All_the_Talents] (1806‑1807).  

---

## Later political activity  

During the **Regency Crisis** of 1788‑89, Fitzwilliam opposed a popular address supporting the Prince of Wales, deeming it “a very hazardous experiment” [33]. He continued to wield influence in the Lords, moving amendments on **peace motions** with France and defending the **Habeas Corpus Suspension Act 1794** [Habeas_Corpus_Suspension_Act_1794] as necessary for national security.  

In the 1790s he became increasingly concerned about the spread of **Jacobinism** in Britain, warning of “the red‑hot principles” that could destabilise the nation [61‑62]. He supported the **Seditious Meetings Act 1795** [Seditious_Meetings_Act_1795] but later grew skeptical of its permanence, calling it “a temporary measure” that would “operate an essential alteration in the constitution” [159].  

During the **Peterloo Massacre** of 1819, Fitzwilliam’s initial reaction was cautious; he wrote that “the military are henceforward the governing power in the British Empire” [162]. He later advocated for inquiries into the use of military force against civilian assemblies, fearing a precedent that could erode civil authority.  

---

## Legacy and assessments  

**Lord Holland** [Henry_Vassall-Fox,_3rd_Baron_Holland] summed up Fitzwilliam as “a striking instance of that most agreeable truth—that courage and honesty in great situations more than supply the place of policy or talent.” He argued that Fitzwilliam’s influence derived not from his titles or fortune but from his “goodness and generosity, and from the combination of gentleness and courage which distinguished his amiable and unpretending character” [181].  

Historian **E. A. Smith** highlighted Fitzwilliam as “the typical eighteenth‑century aristocrat—a man to whom politics was a natural responsibility due to his order, his family and his country, but not a field for the display of ambition.” He saw Fitzwilliam’s world as that of the “great estate owner…agents, tenantry, mortgages, leases and properties were his daily concern” [30].  

